description: Likely from agog; it appeared first as on gog. Attested from the 16th to 18th centuries. Compare French gogue (“sprightliness”), and Welsh gogi (“to agitate, shake”).

examples: 1812 [1639],  John Fletcher,  “Wit Without Money”, in  The Works of Beaumont and Fletcher‎[1], page 65:Nay, you have put me into such a gog of going, I would not stay for all the world.
